refraction.book.start.title=Getting Started

refraction.book.start.hello.title=&a&lRefraction&r
refraction.book.start.hello.desc=Blinded by the Light
refraction.book.start.hello.content1=Hello there, [player]! I'm Eve, your personal assistant! <br> I'm here to help you &m<study phys&kics&r&m>&rlearn how to manipulate light using reflection and refraction!
refraction.book.start.hello.content2=Ever wanted to suck items and entities with a single beam of light? Ever wanted to create a disco ball based quarry? How about creating a laser defense system? Or, heck, maybe you just wanted to make an epic laser show?
refraction.book.start.hello.content3=Well then, [player], welcome to my world of reflection and refraction! You will not be disappointed at the results of mirror arrays and rainbows. Let's get started, shall we?


refraction.book.start.rainbow.title=&a&lThe Rainbow&r
refraction.book.start.rainbow.desc=RGB
refraction.book.start.rainbow.content1=I'm first going to start off by teaching you the very concept and nature of light manipulation, so to start off: Light is made up of 3 primary colors: &c&lRed&r, &a&lGreen&r, and &1&lBlue&r. They are often merged into the familiar phrase '&c&lR&a&lG&1&lB&r'. You will base your color merging knowledge on those 3 primary colors.
refraction.book.start.rainbow.content2=Light also has a strength, or in more technical terms is called 'alpha value'. In this mod, we represented this value as the 'white bar' indicating power/strength/amount/alpha or whatever you want to call it.
refraction.book.start.rainbow.content3=So now we have RGB and A (or RGBA). You start off with a white beam (which we will get to later in [Baby Steps]). A white beam or white color in general is a color mix of all three primary colors. It contains red, green, and blue in equal amounts merged.
refraction.book.start.rainbow.content4=You will be basing your work on this knowledge because you want to acquire the many different colors from white beams which will be split (later on).
refraction.book.start.rainbow.content5=The way we represent the rgb values (in recipes and the &1&lSpectrometer&r) is using ratios. So if the &1&lSpectrometer&r is showing half red and half blue, it means it doesn't matter 'how much of blue and red in values' you have, it means that you just need a perfectly equal amount of both with respect to each other.
refraction.book.start.rainbow.content6=The value that DOES matter and not as a ratio is the white bar which indicates alpha/strength/amount. You can see the recipe of the Reflection Chamber on the right tab to see an example of the bars viewed in the recipes.
refraction.book.start.rainbow.content7=&c&l[!FOR FUTURE REFERENCE!]&r <br> Solar alpha/strength (used in magnifiers): [config:solar_strength] <br> Glowstone alpha/strength (used in laser blocks): [config:glowstone_strength]

refraction.book.start.baby.title=&a&lBaby Steps&r
refraction.book.start.baby.desc=Initial Setup
refraction.book.start.baby.content1=Ok, let's see here... Ah, yes. So you'll first want to make an &1&lAssembly Table&r. This simple block will help you craft everything you need. I will guide you through the steps of its usage when we get to that. For now, craft one. It requires 7 iron ingots and 1 &1&lLens&r.
refraction.book.start.baby.content2=Next, you'll want to craft a &1&lMagnifier&r. When provided with a 3x3 of &1&lLens& blocks above it - provided that they have a line of sight to the sky - it will converge the sunlight into a focused beam of light directly below it.
refraction.book.start.baby.content3=I should note that you should place the &1&lMagnifier&r (with the lens blocks above it) anywhere above the &1&lAssembly Table&r. This will be a one time setup to get you the basic items and can be altered after we're done with the second step.

refraction.book.start.shiny.title=&a&lOooh, Shinyr&
refraction.book.start.shiny.desc=asda.
refraction.book.start.shiny.content1=Neither gold nor iron have the reflective properties you'd want to be able to play around with light, but they both are a step in the right direction. To get something very reflective, craft an iron ingot with a gold ingot in a regular crafting window. It'll give you a highly &1&lReflective Alloy&r, very useful for light manipulation.

refraction.book.start.reflection.title=&a&lReflection&r
refraction.book.start.reflection.desc=Mirror Array
refraction.book.start.reflection.content1=Now that you have more reflective resources, you can dispense with the annoyance of placing &1&lMagnifier&r exactly above the table. By creating a Mirror with &1&lReflective Alloys&r and rotating it using a &1&lScrewdriver&r you can redirect beams to any direction.
refraction.book.start.reflection.content2=You can craft a &1&lMirror&r using the assembly table you crafted. The &1&lAssembly Table&r will allow you to make such materials, by using magnifiers to focus beams into it and providing a &lredstone signal&r, it will fuse the items inside of it together provided the beams being pointed into it evaluate to the correct color range and add up to the proper beam strength value (that also has a max and min per recipe).
refraction.book.start.reflection.content3=&lIN LAYMAN'S TERMS:&r Each assembly table recipe requires different colored beams to be pointed at it and a specific alpha value range that needs to be met for it to be able to craft your item.&r
refraction.book.start.reflection.content4=If you focus multiple beams into an assembly table, it'll be able to do more intense recipes, granting you more components to play with which you can read about later. For now, let me tell you how to craft the mirror:
refraction.book.start.reflection.content5=To figure out how many beams you need pointed at the assembly table to craft this, take the minimum alpha value the mirror requires in it's recipe and divide it by the alpha strength of the &1&lMagnifiers&r ( [config:solar_strength] ) . This is the amount of beams you need to point at the assembly table.
refraction.book.start.reflection.content6=If the packmaker has not tampered with the recipe of this, the mirror should require one beam. Do double check.
refraction.book.start.reflection.content7=And if the packmaker hasn't tampered with the color values of the recipe as well, the recipe should only require a white beam since its recipe requires 255 of all 3 colors (red, green, blue) and requires an alpha value of [config:solar_strength]. Luckily, you presumably already made a setup for that!
refraction.book.start.reflection.content8=Feed the table the items by right clicking it and &lpowering it with a redstone signal&r. Red particles will signal progress, a green flash will signal completion And now that you have a mirror:
refraction.book.start.reflection.content9=Using the &1&lScrewdriver&r on the air will decrease its precision, and sneak-using it will increase its precision. Using it on a mirror's top will rotate it horizontally, and on a mirror's side will rotate it vertically.

refraction.book.start.refraction.title=&a&lRefraction&r
refraction.book.start.refraction.desc=TODO
refraction.book.start.refraction.content1=So far, you've only witnessed thin white beams, let's change it up a bit!
refraction.book.start.refraction.content2=Different colors of beams can produce some effects. These effects can be highly beneficial to your needs, or just plain fun. I'll get to these effects later on, but to acquire them, you'll want to craft yourself a &1&lPrism&r.
refraction.book.start.refraction.content3=This particular block will split a light beam into it's three basic colors: red, green, and blue. We'll get to the effects of these colors later on, as I've already said, but to acquire this block, you'll want a minimum of 2 mirrors all pointing into the assembly table with beams from magnifiers on each of them.
refraction.book.start.refraction.content4=Next, right click the &1&lAssembly Table&r with 6 &1&lLens&r blocks to input the items and provide a redstone signal to the table and it will craft you your first &1&lPrism&r
refraction.book.start.refraction.content5=&c&l[!] WARNING [!]&r Do NOT place the &1&lPrism&r in front of a beam just yet. Please read the next section before proceeding because the next part can be lethal to both your person and your surroundings if caution is not taken!

refraction.book.start.rgb.title=&a&lRGB&r
refraction.book.start.rgb.desc=Prism Splitting
refraction.book.start.rgb.content1=Now, I know what you might be thinking: Eve, what the crap are the effects, what do they look like, and how do I use them already?! Ok, so first off: I'm just doing my job calm down. I NEED to give you the precautions and warnings beforehand. Anyways, I'll stop babbling and start:
refraction.book.start.rgb.content2=As I've said above, a &1&lPrism&r will split light beams into 3 separate colors: red, green, and blue. All three have separate effects which are the following: The blue beam is a freeze effect. It will slow you down when it's at low strength. Higher strengths include blindness, nausea, weakenss, etc..
refraction.book.start.rgb.content3=The green beam is a bonemeal beam. If pointed at a bonemealable block, it has a chance based on it's strength to bonemeal the block
refraction.book.start.rgb.content4=And now comes the most dangerous part... The red beam is a burn beam. It has a chance based on it's strength to set any block it touches on fire and any entity it touches aflame. This beam is &lextremely&r dangerous if not created with caution because it can and WILL burn down your surroundings easily if you are not careful. This is especially true because of the green beam, because if an area gets bonemealed and burnt, it will cause tons of fire based damage to your area.
refraction.book.start.rgb.content5=The moment you place down the prism, all 3 of these beams will be split and refracted outwards. Be VERY careful that you are in a safe, burn free zone.

refraction.book.start.effects.title=&a&lEffects&r
refraction.book.start.effects.desc=Beam Merging
refraction.book.start.effects.content1=So, if you haven't burnt down your area already, let's get to the more notable effects. You can get the rest of the effects from the mod using a &1&lReflection Chamber&r.
refraction.book.start.effects.content2=This block will merge any two or more beams that intersect with it and produce a final beam based on the weighted average of all the colors that went into it, taking into account color strength as well as outputting the beam in an averaged angle between them all.
refraction.book.start.effects.content3=This block is extremely useful as it is able to produce the entire color spectrum if used right. You'll want it to use the rest of the effects in the mod, which are: 
refraction.book.start.effects.content4=Cyan: Attract entities (items). If the beam is strong enough, it will attract any living entity.
refraction.book.start.effects.content5=Magenta: Disperse entities (items). If the beam is strong enough, it will disperse any living entity.
refraction.book.start.effects.content6=Yellow: Has a chance, based on strength, to break blocks it touches.
refraction.book.start.effects.content7=Pink: Has a chance, based on strength, to place a block that it intersects with in item form.
refraction.book.start.effects.content8=Orange: When pointed at a redstone component, will power it. Has to have at least 1 air block available anywhere around the block it's pointing at. Also will respect the side of the redstone component it hits. Redstone power output depends on potency .

refraction.book.start.merging.title=&a&lMerging&r
refraction.book.start.merging.desc=TODO
refraction.book.start.merging.content1=Due to much confusion relating to the crafting of blocks, I shall guide you on how to make the &1&lReflaction Chamber&r step by step to help you out.
refraction.book.start.merging.content2=First of all, looking at the recipe: it requires 'half green' (since we work with ratios in the 3 colors), no blue, and full red. IE: We need twice as much red than green.
refraction.book.start.merging.content3=When you split a beam in a prism into 3 beams (red, green and blue), the alpha value of the original beam also splits. So each of the 3 colored beams you have are each [config:solar_strength] / 3. So you'll need to take this into account to get enough summative alpha into the assembly table.
refraction.book.start.merging.content4=If the pack author has not tampered with anything: The default solar alpha of magnifiers is 16, so 16 / 3 = ~5. The cube's recipe requires a MINIMUM of 16, so we need at least (16 / 5) ~3.2 beams into the table. So round up to 4 beams.
refraction.book.start.merging.content5=So now that we know we need 4 beams minimum to match the alpha range of the cube, we need to match the color, so:
refraction.book.start.merging.content6=Half green, full red, no blue. That means do not point any blue beams into the table, and point twice the red as that of green or more.
refraction.book.start.merging.content7=But if you notice carefully: The green beam needs a maximum of 160. So you can point 2 green beams and 2 red beams to acquire what you need.
refraction.book.start.merging.content8=Next just input your items and power it. Done!

refraction.book.items.title=Items

refraction.book.items.screw.title=&a&lScrewdriver&r
refraction.book.items.screw.desc=TODO
refraction.book.items.screw.content1=You've already supposedly read and used the &1&lScrewdriver&r, but to recap:
refraction.book.items.screw.content2=Right click the air to increment it's angle. Shift right click to decrement. Right click the top or bottom of a mirror/splitter to rotate it around the y-axis. Shift right click to reverse the rotation
refraction.book.items.screw.content4=Right click the sides of a &1&lMirror&r/&1&lSplitter&r to rotate it around the x-axis. Shift right click to reverse the rotation.
refraction.book.items.screw.content5=Setting the angle and placing the &1&lScrewdriver&r in a dispenser facing a mirror then powering it (INDIRECTLY - read warning) will change the mirror's angle as if you right clicked it on the face the dispenser is hitting.
refraction.book.items.screw.content6=To invert the dispenser as if it's shift right clicking the screw driver, put the screwdriver into a crafting gird. The output of the recipe will be an 'inverted' screwdriver that will do what you want on dispensers and vice versa to reinvert it.
refraction.book.items.screw.content7=&c&l[!] WARNING [!]&r Powering a dispenser with a screwdriver with a direct line of redstone power to adjust a mirror might seem glitchy. This is because powering a mirror will set it's angle to it's 'powered' state and vice versa. To fix this, simply power the dispenser INDIRECTLY through a block.

refraction.book.items.alloy.title=&a&lReflective Alloy&r
refraction.book.items.alloy.desc=TODO
refraction.book.items.alloy.content1=You've already seen the &1&lReflective Alloy&r ingots, but what you didn't know is that it has a block variation. The block form of this alloy will reflect/bounce all beams that intersect with it in the cardinal direction hit. In a way, it's sort of a cheap precisionless mirror. This block is considered as great protection against volatile or dangerous beams.
refraction.book.items.alloy.content2=You can also craft reflective alloy armor with this ingot. Each piece will decrease the potency of any beam effect that hits you. A full set wont completely negate effects, but you will become a walking mirror. IE: Beams will literally bounce and reflect off of you in the direction you face.


