refraction.book.items.grenade.title=&a&lPhoton Grenades&r
refraction.book.items.grenade.desc=TODO
refraction.book.items.grenade.content1=When placed into an &1&lAssembly Table&r with any beam hitting it, it will infuse the grenade with that color. When thrown, the grenade will explode violently with the color (taking into account the original strength as well)


refraction.book.items.cannon.title=&a&lPhoton Cannon&r
refraction.book.items.cannon.desc=TODO
refraction.book.items.cannon.content1=The &1&lPhoton Cannon&r is a gun that continuously fires a beam provided you have a Light Cartridge in your inventory.
refraction.book.items.cannon.content2=When holding the gun, the bar on the right side of your HUD will show up indicating the fuel or amount of ammo left in the loaded cartridge.
refraction.book.items.cannon.content3=You can hold multiple cartridges in your inventory at once. To swap which color the gun will use, hold the gun, then scroll while sneaking. You will flip through the colors and can stop at any one to choose the color desired.
refraction.book.items.cannon.content4=It is worth noting that the hud on the right, indicating fuel or amount of energy left per color, is a sum of all the cartridges with the same color available in your inventory.


refraction.book.blocks.title=Blocks

refraction.book.blocks.laser.title=&a&lLaser / Electric Laser&r
refraction.book.blocks.laser.desc=TODO
refraction.book.blocks.laser.content1=The &1&lLaser&r block, when fed with glowstone, will produce a light beam that lasts for 25 seconds. This block is different from a magnifier in that it's beam is 4x more powerful in strength than a &1&lMagnifier&r.
refraction.book.blocks.laser.content2=You can insert glowstone into it by either right clicking on it or pointing a hopper into it. If you want to continually power it automatically, consider a witch farm or a mob farm that filters witches.
refraction.book.blocks.laser.content3=The Electric Laster block is like the regular laser block. The only difference is that it accepts tesla/forge energy instead of glowstone.

refraction.book.blocks.mirror.title=&a&lMirrors / Splitter&r
refraction.book.blocks.mirror.desc=TODO
refraction.book.blocks.mirror.content1=This &1&lSplitter&r block is a half-mirror. It has the same properties as a mirror, but instead of reflecting a beam directly, the beam will be split into 2 halves. One is reflected like that of a normal mirror, and the other half phases right through the beam.


refraction.book.blocks.disco.title=&a&lDisco Ball&r
refraction.book.blocks.disco.desc=TODO
refraction.book.blocks.disco.content1=The DiscoBall is one of the most interesting blocks in the mod. When this block receives a redstone signal, it will start spinning (it's a disco ball after all).
refraction.book.blocks.disco.content2=When a beam hits this block while it's active, it will spread the beam in all directions. This results in some very very interesting behavior. This can also be considered to be one of the most powerful and most dangerous blocks in the mod. You can point any beam into it and it will produce smaller beams of that color in every single direction.
refraction.book.blocks.disco.content3=You could point a burn beam at it and it'll burn everything surrounding it, or point a yellow beam and have it become a circular quarry.
refraction.book.blocks.disco.content4=&c&l[!] WARNING [!]&r It is HIGHLY recommended you surround the block with reflective alloy blocks to avoid potential disasters from occuring.


refraction.book.blocks.sensor.title=&a&lSensor&r
refraction.book.blocks.sensor.desc=TODO
refraction.book.blocks.sensor.content1=This little dongle of a block will produce a flashing redstone signal against the block it's placed against. You can get a full continuous signal with 1 repeater from it but it's a good compact clock block otherwise when a beam intersects with it. Moreover, beams will phase directly through it for convenience.


refraction.book.blocks.fiber.title=&a&lOptic Fiber&r
refraction.book.blocks.fiber.desc=TODO
refraction.book.blocks.fiber.content1=&1&lOptic fiber&r cables are very important cabling here. Any beam pointed at one end of an &1&lOptic Fiber&r cable will output the beam at the other end of the cable whilst also adjusting it to the cardinal direction it's facing with absolutely no loss.
refraction.book.blocks.fiber.content2=One of the 2 cable facings will always face the direction you place it against for convenience. No more than 2 connections can be made per fiber optic cable, so it cannot split beams.
refraction.book.blocks.fiber.content3=These cables are also useful when working with &1&lReflection Chambers&r. If you place a cable against the face of a reflection chamber - provided that the angle of the output beam from the &1&lReflection Chamber&r is from the face the cable is against - it will output the beam straight to the cable, directly adjusting it to a cardinal direction.


refraction.book.blocks.spectro.title=&a&lSpectrometer&r
refraction.book.blocks.spectro.desc=TODO
refraction.book.blocks.spectro.content1=The &1&lSpectrometer&r is a block that can show you the strength of each individual array of color from a beam intersecting with the block. It will show you red, green, blue, and white bars on its face indicating the rgb values of the beams hitting it as well as white acting as beam strength.


refraction.book.blocks.exciter.title=&a&lElectron Exciter&r
refraction.book.blocks.exciter.desc=TODO
refraction.book.blocks.exciter.content1=Our friends at aperture science have provided us with their amazing technology of hard light bridges!
refraction.book.blocks.exciter.content2=By pointing 2 (or more) attraction (cyan) beams perfectly parallel and pointing straight into 2 adjacent &1&lElectron Exciters&r, a bridge made out of pure light will form between them.
refraction.book.blocks.exciter.content3=This bridge is indestructible, and therefore great for a plethora of uses. You can stack multiple bridges next to each other and in any direction.
refraction.book.blocks.exciter.content4=My friend, GlAdOs, told me to send you this message: 'These bridges are made from natural light that we pumped in from the surface. If you rubbed your cheek on one, it would be like standing outside with the sun shining on your face. It would also set your hair on fire, so don't actually do it.


refraction.book.blocks.axyz.title=&a&lAXYZ&r
refraction.book.blocks.axyz.desc=TODO
refraction.book.blocks.axyz.content1=I was told that this technology isn't quite advanced enough yet, as it can generate wormholes, but only photons can pass through, while matter, on the other hand, cannot. Any beam that goes in will come out the other end, but the wormhole isn’t stable enough to work the other way around. The tear in space and time isn't big nor powerful enough to do anything but transport beams.
refraction.book.blocks.axyz.content2=The mechanics of this device are unusual to say the least. It says here that you need to feed a dispersion beam (magenta) into a &1&lTranslocator&r pointed directly at the generator, via fiber optic cables hooked into the translocator.
refraction.book.blocks.axyz.content3=Apparently, passing a dispersion beam through the translocator will cause it to affect the wormhole generator, causing the generator to be pushed directly away from the translocator. What seems to be happening here is that you are displacing the wormhole generator, but not the other end of the wormhole, allowing you to separate the two ends. 
refraction.book.blocks.axyz.content4=The &1&lAXYZ&r is also pushable by a piston. Unlike using a dispersion beam, pushing the wormhole generator via a piston will also move the bound wormhole. Therefore, the wormhole will shift in the same direction in which the generator is pushed. A 'quantum entanglement' of sorts.
refraction.book.blocks.axyz.content5=By repeating the process of using teleposers and pistons on the generator, you can treat the generator like a 'cursor' to move the wormhole freely in the world. This can allow for some more advanced machines such as automatically moving quarries.


